these two books and the words that filled them were the balm I didn’t know I need or could have. 

how seen i felt with every turn of page.

how soothing it was to have some of my deepest and hidden emotions brought forward and articulated in ways i never would have had the capacity.

and it genuinely felt like Brand was conversing with Lorde as I read these two back to back... it just made the experience all the more great.

i’m currently reading Tessa McWatt’s Shame on Me and she used the word ‘continuity’ to describe what she sought out of her ancestry.

McWatt’s use of the word Continuity really helped me frame what I loved so much about A Map to the Door of No Return and Sister Outsider because they explored that desire—that lack—and challenged its necessity to us as Black people, particularly Black women, in the diaspora. How easily this desire has mutated and been exploited as a means to uphold the institutions and systems that destroy us. As Lorde famously said, “the master’s tools will never dismantle the master’s house.” 

all this to say, 1000000000000000/10 recommending these two, i will be revisiting them often. McWatt’s Shame on Me is also pretty great (in a “in my light skin feels” type of way, i will not lie 😂)
 
Happy Friday everyone, hope you all have a great weekend 😊!
